To find the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},$ we use the formula $\text{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} = \left(\dfrac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \right\|^2}\right) \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$

First, we compute the dot product $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = 4 \cdot 2 + 5 \cdot 0 = 8.$

Next, we compute the magnitude squared $\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \right\|^2 = 2^2 + 0^2 = 4.$

Substituting these values into the formula, we have $\text{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} = \left(\dfrac{8}{4}\right) \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = 2 \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}.$

We can verify this result by noting that the projection of any vector onto the span of a vector is a scalar multiple of that vector. In this case, the span of $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is the x-axis, so the projection is along the x-axis, which is why the y-component is zero. Therefore, the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is indeed $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}.$

Confidence: 100% Step 1: Find the dot product of the two vectors. \begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} &= 4 \cdot 2 + 5 \cdot 0 \\
&= 8
\end{align*}

Step 2: Find the magnitude squared of the vector onto which we are projecting.

\begin{align*}
\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \right\|^2 &= 2^2 + 0^2 \\
&= 4
\end{align*}

Step 3: Compute the scalar projection factor.

\begin{align*}
\frac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \right\|^2} &= \frac{8}{4} \\
&= 2
\end{align*}

Step 4: Multiply the scalar projection factor by the vector onto which we are projecting.

\begin{align*}
\text{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} &= 2 \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

Step 5: Verify the results by noting that the projection of any vector onto the span of a vector is a scalar multiple of that vector. In this case, the span of $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is the x-axis, so the projection is along the x-axis, which is why the y-component is zero. Therefore, the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is indeed $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}.$

